{"questionId":"27764","questionHtml":"<p>Hence, find the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>166666</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>≈</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>167</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>,&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>,</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>333333</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>≈</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>333</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A2</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong> </em>if only two of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> are correct.<br>Only award <em><strong>FT</strong></em> if three linear equations, each in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;are stated in part (b) (ii) or (iii).<br>Award <em><strong>A2FT</strong></em> for their&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.<br>Award <em><strong>A1FT</strong></em> for their&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27764","referenceCode":"22N.3.AHL.TZ0.1b.iii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, find the values of a1, a2 and a3.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"b.iii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.16—Solution of systems of linear equations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}